2500|$|After the 2000 United States Census, the Michigan Legislature reconfigured the state's congressional map. In the process, they redrew the 10th District, {{represented}} by 13-term Democrat <b>David</b> <b>Bonior.</b> The old 10th {{had been a}} fairly compact district taking in most of Macomb and St. Clair counties. However, the reconfigured 10th was pushed {{all the way to}} the Thumb. In the process, the legislature moved Miller's home in Harrison Township into the district, while shifting Bonior's home in Mount Clemens to the neighboring 12th District. Bonior opted to run for the governor of Michigan rather than run for re-election to the House of Representatives. Miller won the Republican primary, and in the general election in November she handily beat Carl Marlinga, the Macomb County Prosecutor since 1982. Marlinga called himself a [...] "Hubert Humphrey Democrat", and Miller called herself a [...] "George W. Bush Republican." [...] She outraised Marlinga, and secured the Teamsters Union (but not AFL-CIO) endorsement.|$|E
25|$|In {{her first}} bid for public office, Miller lost to Democrat <b>David</b> E. <b>Bonior</b> for Michigan's 12th congressional district.|$|R
